EAST SIDE UNION HIGH SCHOOL DISTRICT
	 
Item:  9.04
				 
					 
TO:
Board of Trustees
					 
					 
FROM:  
Dan Moser, Superintendent
					 
					 
PREPARED BY:
Cathy Giammona, Associate Superintendent, Human Resources and Instruction, and Kirsten King, Director of Instructional Services
SUBJECT:
Consideration of Petition for Proposed Green Technology Academy Charter School
	 
Public Hearing To Consider Support For Petition
On June 24, 2011, the District received a charter school petition from the Community Revitalization & Education Agency (“CREA”) Green Technology Academy (“the Petition”). Within 30 days of receiving a charter school petition, the District is required, pursuant to Education Code Section 47605(b) to “hold a public hearing on the provisions of the charter, at which time the governing board of the school district shall consider the level of support for the petition by teachers employed by the district, other employees of the district, and parents.” Upon receipt of the Petition, the District entered into an agreement with representatives from CREA to extend the timeline for conducting the public hearing an additional 60-days, given that the next Board meeting was scheduled for August 30, 2011. Accordingly, the District held a public hearing on the Petition during the public session portion of its regularly scheduled Board meeting on August 30, 2011.
	 
No District employees, members of the public, or representatives from CREA Green Technology Academy spoke at the hearing in support of the charter school.  
	 
Board Decision to Grant Or Deny Petition Must Be Based On Specific Factual Findings
The District must take action to either grant or deny the charter at its September 15, 2011 Board meeting.  The District may grant the charter “if it is satisfied that granting the charter is consistent with sound educational practice.”  The District may not deny a petition for the establishment of a charter school unless it makes factual findings, specific to the particular petition, setting forth specific facts to support one or more of the following findings:
	 
1.  The charter school presents an unsound educational program for the pupils to be enrolled in the charter school.
2.  The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the petition;
3.  The petition does not contain the required number of signatures;
4.  The petition does not contain an affirmation of each of the required conditions set forth in Section 47605(d); or
5.  The petition does not contain reasonably comprehensive descriptions of all of the following:
	 
     (a) Educational Programs;
     (b) Measurable pupil outcomes;
     (c) Measurement of Students Progress;
     (d) Governance Structure Progress;
     (e) Employee qualifications;
     (f) Procedures to Ensure Health and safety;
     (g) Racial and Ethnic Balance;
     (h) Admission Requirements;
     (i) Financial Accountability and Audits;
     (j) Student Suspension/Expulsion Procedures;
     (k) Retirement System;
     (l) Student Attendance Alternatives;
     (m) Employee Rights;
     (n) Dispute Resolution;
     (o) Exclusive Public School Employer; and
     (p) School Closure Protocol.
	   
	 
FISCAL IMPACT:
There will be a fiscal impact.  The anticipated fiscal impact is not subject to quantification at this time due to the significant uncertainties in the actual charter operations and the extent to which the charter school draws upon non-reimbursable District services.
	 
FUNDING SOURCE:
General Fund
	 
RECOMMENDATION:
It is recommended that the Board of Trustees give careful consideration to this Petition and the concerns raised by the Charter Petition Review Team.  If the Board acts to deny the Petition, the Board should adopt the attached Charter Petition Review Team Report and the findings included therein.
